article.description:
The Denver Nuggets discovered a new level 
of offensive ineptitude.
article.headline: Denver offense struggles to score 65 points
article.linkText: Suns take care of business in win over Nuggets
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- The Phoenix Suns couldn't afford a letdown against an inferior opponent as they did so many times earlier this season. They took care of business Tuesday night against the Denver Nuggets.
 
Marion
Shawn Marion scored 24 of his 33 points in the second half and the Suns tied a team record for fewest points by an opponent, defeating the Nuggets 95-65. "A team that had given us problems all year, I was very happy to see that from start to finish we stayed with our intensity and our focus because we knew what they were capable of doing when they get down large, double-digit leads; they've come back quite a few times," Phoenix coach Frank Johnson said. The Suns moved one game ahead of the idle Houston Rockets in the race for the eighth and final playoff berth in the Western Conference. Each team has eight games remaining. Phoenix's smothering defense -- it often attacked Denver in the backcourt -- limited the Nuggets to a .263 shooting percentage, the lowest in Suns history. The previous low was .269 by Cleveland on Nov. 5, 1971. The Nuggets' 20 field goals were the fewest by any team in the league this season. Previously, the low was 21, accomplished four times. "I thought our defensive pressure was good," Johnson said. "We followed our defensive game plan to a 'T' and forced a lot of turnovers." Phoenix also had its biggest winning margin of the season. The previous best was 26 in a 109-83 victory over Washington on March 21. Denver's loss was its sixth straight away from home and dropped its road record to 4-34, the worst in the Western Conference. Marion connected for 15 points in the third period, including four 3-pointers, as the Suns increased a 14-point halftime lead to 68-49. Marion, however, preferred to talk about the team's defense rather than his offense. "Defensively, we started from the get-go and kept it up all the way..." he said. "We got ourselves a good win and that's what our goal was." The Suns now are 16-16 against teams with losing records. Amare Stoudemire added 16 points for the Suns and Penny Hardaway had 12. All 11 players who were in the game for Phoenix scored. Nikoloz Tskitishvili, Nene Hilario and reserve Marcus Camby each scored 10 points for the Nuggets. "It was very glaring in terms of not being able to handle the basketball, pass the basketball and shoot the basketball," Denver coach Jeff Bzdelik said. "Nobody shot the ball well. They got up and exposed our inability to pass the basketball. "It was a very disappointing and embarrassing loss." The lowly Nuggets shot a miserable 21 percent (4-for-19) in the first period, making as many 3-point field goals (two) as 2-pointers. They didn't hit their first 2-pointer until Camby connected on a 17-foot jumper with 2:44 left in the quarter. The Suns, meanwhile, were 10-for-18 (55 percent), and in a rarity, had an assist on each basket, to open a 28-14 lead. During an 8:02 stretch, the Nuggets went without a field goal, making only five foul shots. At halftime, the Suns led 44-30, the Nuggets' point total representing a season low for a Phoenix opponent this season. Camby was the only effective Denver player in the half, scoring 10 points on 5-of-7 shooting. The Nuggets' starting five shot 3-for-25, including 1-for-10 by Juwan Howard. Howard, the Nuggets' leading scorer, finished 3-for-18 and six points. Game notes
The teams met twice in the first 11 games of the season but hadn't faced each other in more than four months . Now, they will meet twice in four games, with their final meeting of the season next Tuesday night at Denver. ... In the previous game between the teams at America West Arena, the Suns appeared to have won when Marion's putback dunk with six-tenths of a second remaining gave Phoenix a 79-78 lead. But Donnell Harvey threw a length-of-the-court pass to Ryan Bowen for a layup just before the final buzzer and Denver won 80-79. ... Bowen did not play Tuesday night, sidelined with injuries to his sternum and abdomen. ... The Nuggets are the lowest scoring team in the league (84.0), last in free throw percentage (.695) and last in 3-point field goal percentage (.279). ... Phoenix also held the Chicago Bulls to 65 points on March 6, 1975, winning 88-65. The previous low for a Suns' opponent this season was 72, by Denver on Nov. 13.
